@node funny "6.1 Them funny bugs no-one likes to talk about :)"

This section has been written for a bit of a laff. Its just a list of funny
bugs that sprung up before MegaBook 4.0 was released but were fixed so no1
saw em :) 

 o This has to be the ALL TIME BEST bug :) Development was going really well
   and I was just updating the file format to handle the new features. Then,
   all of a sudden MegaBook crashed. Not that surprising, you may think, but
   i hadnt even run it yet! The compiler was spewing for some reason I couldnt
   find at all. It took me 2 days to find what was wrong and crashing Dice,
   eventually I discovered a call was being prototyped after it was defined
   and Dice didnt like it at all ... nasty!
 
 o Another nasty one ... suddenly notes stopped working and started dumping
   the entire memory to T:. To this day I still dont know why it does it,
   but it only seems to do it when i activate the current project after an
   open. This has been extensively tested and retested and I still cant find
   the reason why, but never mind, it works as it is for now, so Ill leave
   it and come back to it when I have less to do. Excpect fixes in 3008 :)

 o Another quite funny one. The first generation macro recorder (i.e. my
   first attempt) worked extremely well. Except for when a ARexx command
   needed arguments. I forgot to write the name of the command, so some 
   commands ended up as memory dumps. One such example is the recorder
   saving parts of the assembly source (the source generated by the C
   compiler, that is) into the arexx script. 
 
These are from MegaBook 3.2
 
 o Due to me being tired when i recoded the toolbar, i forgot to remove the
   font adaptivity. This led to some funny side effects when the system font
   wasn't topaz :) We had mis-sized gadgets with the images staying the same
   size and overlapping everything :)
   
 o In another bout of stupidness i COMPLETELY forgot to call the iconify
   handling code so when u iconified, nothing was checking for the close
   gadget :) It took me a few hours to find what was wrong :((

@endnode

@node oldreguse "Registered Users Readme"

Im sure by now people are wondering why i suddenly went quiet and stopped
writing and replying to emails. No, Im not dead :) I just had a major system
problem and lost ALL the mailing list stuff and consequentially, everybody's
email addresses got lost :( If you were a previously registered user, please
send me your email address again. The address is still the same,
megabook@dvalley.demon.co.uk but the mailing list is down untill i get the
email addresses again.

To the people who have sent me registrations between the time the crash
happened and this release, and also those who registered for Version 3.x,
i still have your email addresses (3.x ones were stored elsewhere, and the
latest ones are currently waiting to be looked at properly) so you lucky lot
will be hearing from me shortly after this is released, and told about the
release and what to do about the address problems. You will probably have
that email by the time you are reading this anyway. Also, to clear up any
questions you may have, regardless of whether you received a reply or not,
if i got the registration form then i consider you a registered user.

To everybody who was on the old mailing list BEFORE i moved over to majordomo
(i.e. all the messages with "sorry i havent got the list up yet" kinda things)
If you have saved any of those messages, they have the list of recipients
in the headers. If you still have them, please send me the To: and Cc: headers
so i can start to rebuild the list!

@endnode

@node readthis "MegaBook's Future"

MegaBook is a constantly changing program. Those that have been using MegaBook
since before Version 4 was released will know this already. MegaBook has
turned into the largest, most popular, and most of all most fun project Ive
had the pleasure to work with. Not even I could predict what has happened
to MegaBook, its changed beyond recognition and has way superceded what I
envisioned it to be. I set out to create the best Amiga address book and
now, 3 years later, that goal has been more then achieved. Even Amiga Format
agrees, one of the UK's biggest Amiga magazines! We've even got on the
coverdisks of a couple of German Amiga magazines, and some others. 

The future for MegaBook certainly looks vey bright, and this section of the
guide is here to tell you about it.

MegaBook 4.2 reflects upon what is to come. It introduces some new features
that are the start of even more new stuff for MegaBook 4.3, hooks are now
in place for us to add plugin support and many other interesting new features.

Whilst MegaBook is a great program, I feel that it is let down by the
documentation. MegaBook was always easy to use, so the general feeling
around the time Version 3 was released was that documentation didnt need to
be more then a little brief. This guide has been edited and reworked so much
now that its getting to be a pain to edit, and it really lets down MegaBook.
We have started to write new documentation, in a new format. Almost everyone
who uses MegaBook has Internet access, afterall that is the best place to
get MegaBook quickly. Therefore, most of you will also have a Web Browser
so we feel that new documentation needs to take advantage of this. New
documentation will be in HTML format, so you'll need a web browser to get
the best out of it. Of course, we will still include an AmigaGuide version.

Another thing holding MegaBook back is Workbench 2.04. Retaining full
compatibility with that has caused us to drop some features. If you have
ever used MegaBook on Workbench 2.04 and Workbench 3.x, you'll of noticed
that it looks much much better under 3.x. The new versions of MegaBook are
likely to need more of 3.x's features, at the expense of less functionality
under 2.04 but I dont think there are many people left who use that now. If
you use it, and would like to comment on this, please get in touch with me.

The other thing MegaBook doesnt have is a website. We are currently throwing
around ideas for it, but havent got very far yet due to time restrictions.
If anybody has ideas for the website, please send them to me!

For quite some time now, we've been thinking "Why an address book ? why not
a database too ?" ... the answer to this has always been "no time!" untill
now. In writing MegaBook, we've developed some very usefull code ... a 
database engine, project managers, external file I/O, plugins, and much
more. All of these can be reused in other projects of ours. The new year
will probably see early betas of MegaBase, a complete database program for
your Amiga. We intend it to support as much as is possible of every database
ever written. Quite simply, it is a massive project. MegaBook wont suffer
from this at all, it will benefit from it. It will enable us to use a more
powerfull database engine in MegaBook, speeding up access times on large
databases no end! More details on MegaBase are being kept under wraps for
now, I just thought you should know about it!

If you want more information on MegaBook's future or any other part of
MegaBook, please feel free to email us at megabook@dvalley.demon.co.uk

@endnode
